  },
  {
    "id": "dataset=decision_decision_commonwealth_1905_decision_commonwealth_1905_9ff1e908_57",
    "doc_id": "dataset=decision_decision_commonwealth_1905_decision_commonwealth_1905_9ff1e908",
    "original_source_path": "newapp/dataset=decision/decision/commonwealth/1905/decision_commonwealth_1905_9ff1e908.json",
    "text": "I take it Statute in laying down that rule means that all the eireun of the case are to be taken into consideration—the manner publication,and the circumstances under which it was mad as the facts. For instance, it may well be that the publicat a libel to an officer of police is for the public benefit, but publication of the same matter by advertisement in a pi newspaper would not be for the public benefit at all. the publication is for the public benefit or not is a questio fact to be determined by the tribunal before which the east tried. But, if a reasonable man might draw an inference eit way, it cannot be said that there was a want of reasonab probable cause for the proseeutor drawing it in a way advers the accused person.",
    "version_id": "high_court_of_australia:/showbyHandle/1/14123",
    "type": "decision",
    "jurisdiction": "commonwealth",
    "source": "high_court_of_australia",
    "mime": "application/pdf",
    "date": "1905-09-11",
    "citation": "Crowley v Glissan (No 2) [1905] HCA 31",
    "url": "https://eresources.hcourt.gov.au/downloadPdf/1905/HCA/31",
    "when_scraped": "2024-09-15T21:54:37.711348+10:00"
  },
  {
    "id": "dataset=decision_decision_commonwealth_1905_decision_commonwealth_1905_9ff1e908_58",
    "doc_id": "dataset=decision_decision_commonwealth_1905_decision_commonwealth_1905_9ff1e908",
    "original_source_path": "newapp/dataset=decision/decision/commonwealth/1905/decision_commonwealth_1905_9ff1e908.json",
    "text": "That seems to be an obvious application the rule. If a reasonable man might draw the inference that t accused could not successfully set up such a defence, because he was not likely to induce any jury to believe int truth of the allegation, or because he was not likely to in them to believe that it was for the public benefit that the p cation should be made, it cannot be said that there was absence of reasonable and probable cause for the prose (1) A.C., 168, OF AUSTRALIA. be any doubt about these principles. I proceed to apply to the present case. e prosecution was for the publication of a letter.",
    "version_id": "high_court_of_australia:/showbyHandle/1/14123",
    "type": "decision",
    "jurisdiction": "commonwealth",
    "source": "high_court_of_australia",
